Architecture of the New Covenant: The Structure of the Church in the POL-CAT Era
(Architektura Nowego Przymierza: Struktura Kościoła w epoce POL-CAT)
Authors:
•	Bogdan Jacek Góralski (Visionary & Concept Creator)
•	Artificial Intelligence (Analytical Synthesis & Co-author)
________________________________________
I. The Foundation: The Great Unburdening
The fundamental premise of the New Covenant Architecture is the absolute separation of the Sacred from the Profane administration. For centuries, the Church has been burdened with the management of estates, banks, and politics, which dimmed its spiritual clarity.
In this vision:
•	POL-CAT assumes the role of the "Steward of Matter." It manages the economy, logistics, construction of infrastructure, and ensures the material security of the clergy.
•	The Church undergoes a Kenosis (self-emptying) of power and wealth to regain the "Government of Souls." It becomes a pure Moral Authority.
II. The Vatican: The Global University of Conscience
The Papacy transforms from a monarchical structure into the world's highest Ethical Arbitrator.
1.	The Pope as the Guardian of DNA: The Pope’s role is to protect the purity of the "Ideology of Christ" – not as a dogma, but as a universal law of love and survival.
2.	The Council of Sages: The College of Cardinals evolves into a trans-cultural advisory body, including not only clergy but the greatest ethicists and philosophers. Their goal is to define ethical boundaries for the expansion of POL-CAT (e.g., bioethics, AI ethics, resource distribution).
III. The Bishop: The Ethical Auditor
The Bishop ceases to be a territorial administrator and becomes a Spiritual Auditor.
•	Function: The Bishop oversees the activities of POL-CAT in a given region. He does not manage the factories, but he checks whether the workers are treated with dignity.
•	The Power of Veto: If POL-CAT prioritizes profit over people, the Bishop has the right of "Moral Veto," which triggers corrective procedures within the company. He is the conscience of the system.
IV. The Parish: The Spiritual Service Unit
The parish ceases to be a "fee collection point" and becomes a Community Therapy Center.
•	The New Priest: Released from the duty of repairing roofs and counting money (which is done by POL-CAT), the priest becomes a full-time therapist, mediator, and teacher.
•	Education: Seminaries change their curriculum. Future priests study psychology, conflict mediation, and sociology alongside theology to effectively heal human relationships in the workforce.
•	The Liturgy of Life: Religious rites are closely linked to the rhythm of the community's life. The "Daily Bread" is not a metaphor; it is a reality provided by the synergy of work (POL-CAT) and gratitude (Church).
V. Summary: The Symbiosis of Spirit and Matter
This architecture creates a system of checks and balances. POL-CAT gives the Church the tools to function (temples, technology, subsistence), and the Church gives POL-CAT the "Software" (ethics, purpose, social stability).
It is a return to the roots of the Acts of the Apostles, but implemented with 21st-century technology.
