4. Mechanism of Prices, Margins and Work Remuneration in the POL CAT System
4.1. General Assumptions
In the Third Way system, the key role is played by the company POL CAT, which:
•	acts as an ethical distributor of goods and services,
•	operates without classical capital profit,
•	combines in itself:
o	a logistical and commercial function,
o	a scientific and research function,
o	a controlling and stabilizing function for the entire economy.
POL CAT is not “just another private corporation”, but a socio economic institution of public interest whose task is to:
1.	Ensure fair and transparent distribution of goods based on market prices.
2.	Provide decent maintenance for:
o	POL CAT salespeople, responsible for contacts with producers and customers,
o	scientists cooperating with POL CAT, conducting research for the evolution of the system.
3.	Systematically finance science without the mediation of traditional capital profit mechanisms.
The pricing mechanism of POL CAT is designed so as to:
•	not increase prices above the market level,
•	and at the same time replace private profit with:
o	remuneration for salespeople,
o	remuneration for scientists,
o	without creating a class of parasitic capital.
________________________________________
4.2. Principle of Setting the Selling Price
The basic point of reference for POL CAT’s activity is the market price of a product or service.
Let:
•	( C ) denote the total cost of production of a product by the manufacturing company (costs of materials, energy, wages, depreciation, without “owner’s profit”),
•	( P_r ) denote the established market price of a similar product (average price on the domestic or international market),
•	( P_s ) denote the selling price of the product by POL CAT,
•	( M ) denote the POL CAT margin.
In the Third Way system, the following principles are adopted:
1.	POL CAT sells goods and services at the market price: [ P_s = P_r ]
2.	On the value of the market price, a POL CAT margin of 10% is calculated: [ M = 0.10 \times P_r ]
3.	The remaining part of the price (90% of the market price) is used to cover:
o	production costs ( C ),
o	wages of the employees of the manufacturing companies,
o	necessary reserves for investment and modernization,
o	any fees and taxes.
In this way:
•	the consumer pays exactly as much as they would pay on the free market,
•	yet the structure of the price is radically reconstructed in ethical terms:
o	no private capital profit arises,
o	and the POL CAT margin becomes an instrument for maintaining:
	ethical trade,
	independent scientific research.
________________________________________
4.3. Structure of the POL CAT 5% for Salespeople, 5% for Scientists
The total POL CAT margin is 10% of the value of the market price of a product or service.
It is strictly divided into two equal parts:
1.	5% of the market price – allocated to remuneration of POL CAT salespeople.
2.	5% of the market price – allocated to remuneration of scientists working for POL CAT.
This can be written as: [ M = 0.10 \times P_r = M_h + M_n ]
where:
•	( M_h = 0.05 \times P_r ) – the part of the margin allocated to salespeople’s remuneration,
•	( M_n = 0.05 \times P_r ) – the part of the margin allocated to scientists’ remuneration.
As a result:
•	every commercial transaction carried out by POL CAT:
o	maintains a network of ethical salespeople,
o	finances a system of research and analysis that:
	improves the functioning of the economy,
	studies the social effects of reforms,
	develops new technical and organizational solutions.
________________________________________
4.4. Role and Remuneration of POL CAT Salespeople
POL CAT salespeople are persons responsible for:
•	relations with producers and buyers,
•	negotiating contracts,
•	planning deliveries,
•	analyzing market demand,
operating in an ethical system, and not in the logic: “the higher the price, the higher the bonus”.
Remuneration of salespeople comes exclusively from that portion of the margin which is allocated to them: [ M_h = 0.05 \times P_r ]
In practice, this means that:
1.	POL CAT salespeople receive remuneration:
o	linked to the volume of turnover,
o	but with the following principle preserved:
	their average pay cannot significantly exceed the average pay in the entire POL CAT system (principle of ethical equality).
2.	Bonuses for salespeople may depend on such indicators as:
o	timeliness of deliveries,
o	minimization of losses (e.g. waste),
o	satisfaction of contractors,
o	compliance with POL CAT’s ethical rules,
and not on the mere level of prices.
3.	It is forbidden to:
o	covertly increase prices,
o	introduce unfair trading conditions,
o	create hidden margins outside the official system.
In this way:
•	the salesperson ceases to be a “seller of profit”,
•	and becomes a guardian of fair exchange between the producer and society.
________________________________________
4.5. Role and Remuneration of Scientists Working for POL CAT
Scientists cooperating with POL CAT form a research and analytical team, which:
1.	Conducts research:
o	on the economic efficiency of the Third Way system,
o	on the social and cultural consequences of implemented reforms,
o	on technologies that save resources and energy,
o	on models of work organization consistent with the ethics of the Third Way.
2.	Produces analyses and recommendations:
o	for the POL CAT management board,
o	for public administration,
o	for scientific and educational institutions.
3.	Monitors:
o	the level of economic inequalities,
o	the level of employment,
o	the impact of the system on social conflicts,
o	the conformity of practice with ethical assumptions.
Remuneration of scientists comes directly from the part of the [ M_n = 0.05 \times P_r ]
which means that:
•	the larger the economic turnover handled by POL CAT,
•	the larger the resources available for:
o	scientific research,
o	social analyses,
o	pilot projects and socio economic experiments.
At the same time, the following principle applies:
•	scientists’ salaries are:
o	transparent,
o	close to average remuneration within POL CAT,
o	dependent on actual work results (publications, reports, implementations),
o	not allowed to create a “new parasitic elite”.
________________________________________
4.6. Numerical Example of the Mechanism in Operation
To better understand the POL CAT margin mechanism, consider the following example:
•	production cost ( C = 70 ) PLN,
•	market price of a similar product ( P_r = 100 ) PLN.
In the Third Way system:
1.	Selling price by POL CAT: [ P_s = P_r = 100\ \text{PLN} ]
2.	POL CAT margin (10% of the market price): [ M = 0.10 \times 100 = 10\ \text{PLN} ]
3.	Division of the
o	for salespeople’s remuneration: [ M_h = 0.05 \times 100 = 5\ \text{PLN} ]
o	for scientists’ remuneration: [ M_n = 0.05 \times 100 = 5\ \text{PLN} ]
4.	The remaining 90 PLN:
o	is allocated to:
	covering production costs (70 PLN),
	remuneration of the employees of the manufacturing company,
	investment and modernization reserves.
In classical capitalism:
•	the 10 PLN margin could wholly or largely be the owners’ profit.
In the Third Way system:
•	the entire 10 PLN
o	maintains the commercial infrastructure (salespeople),
o	finances scientists who oversee the evolution of the system,
o	does not generate private capital dividends.
________________________________________
4.7. Transparency and Social Control
To prevent distortions of the system, the following principles are introduced:
1.	Full transparency of price structure:
o	for every product distributed by POL CAT, the following information is publicly available:
	market price,
	the 10% margin,
	the division of the margin into:
	remuneration for salespeople (5%),
	remuneration for scientists (5%).
2.	Social and scientific control:
o	over the use of resources from the scientists’ share of the margin is exercised by:
	the POL CAT scientific council (representatives of universities and research institutes),
	a social council (representatives of employees, local governments, civic organizations).
3.	Ban on private capitalization of the
o	funds from the margin may not:
	be paid out as dividends to private shareholders,
	be transformed into private fortunes detached from work.
Thus, POL CAT remains:
•	an institution of work and knowledge,
•	and not an institution of capital.
________________________________________
4.8. Significance of the Margin Mechanism for Social Evolution
The proposed mechanism:
•	5% margin for remuneration of salespeople,
•	5% margin for remuneration of scientists,
has a significance that goes far beyond a technical pricing model. It is an instrument of peaceful social evolution, because it:
1.	Eliminates classical capital profit as a source of individual wealth.
2.	Creates:
o	stable livelihoods for those who:
	organize the exchange of goods (salespeople),
	design and study the system (scientists).
3.	Ensures a continuous feedback loop between:
o	practical economy,
o	and scientific reflection and planning for the future.
4.	Makes it possible that:
o	growth of economic turnover does not become a source of growing inequalities,
o	but a source of growing knowledge and better organization of society.
In this way, the POL CAT price and margin mechanism becomes one of the fundamental tools for implementing the Third Way Concept in Poland and, in the longer term, worldwide.
________________________________________
5. Legal Framework for the Operation of POL CAT
5.1. Legal Nature of POL CAT as a Socio Economic Institution
POL CAT is designed not as an ordinary commercial company driven by capital profit, but as a socio economic institution of public interest. Its legal nature should therefore reflect the following features:
1.	Hybrid character:
o	combining elements of:
	a commercial company (ability to conclude contracts, trade, employ staff),
	a public interest entity (social mission, non profit character in the sense of capital gains),
	a scientific institution (systematic financing of research and analysis).
2.	Statutory public mission:
o	the founding act and statutes of POL CAT shall explicitly state that:
	the primary objective of POL CAT is ethical distribution of goods and services and support for peaceful social evolution through financing science,
	POL CAT does not aim to generate distributable capital profit for private shareholders.
3.	Recognition in law as an institution of special importance:
o	national legislation may grant POL CAT a special status, such as:
	“public interest company”, or
	“ethical distribution institution”,
o	with clear obligations:
	transparency,
	prohibition of capital profit distribution,
	public and scientific oversight.
In legal terms, POL CAT could be established as:
•	a joint stock company of special type, or
•	a new category: socio economic public interest corporation,
with solutions clearly separating:
•	the right to remuneration for work (salespeople, scientists, staff),
•	from the right to capital income (which is excluded or radically limited).
________________________________________
5.2. Ownership Structure and Limitation of Capital Profit
To prevent the creation of a new class of capital owners living off other people’s labour, the legal framework of POL CAT must regulate:
1.	Ownership structure:
o	shares or participation units in POL CAT:
	can be held by:
	employees,
	social and scientific institutions,
	possibly the State or local governments,
	but do not entitle the holder to:
	classical dividends based on profit,
	speculative capital gains detached from work.
2.	Prohibition or strict limitation of dividends:
o	the founding act should provide that:
	any net financial surplus, after covering justified reserves,
cannot be distributed as dividends to shareholders,
	surplus may be used exclusively for:
	strengthening POL CAT’s operational stability,
	investment in infrastructure,
	additional support for research serving the public mission.
3.	Democratic participation of employees and scientific representatives:
o	in the governance bodies of POL CAT:
	employees (including salespeople and scientists) should have:
	representation in the supervisory board,
	influence on the appointment of key management,
	scientific institutions should be represented in advisory councils.
4.	Intergenerational and anti oligarchic safeguards:
o	legal rules should prevent:
	concentration of ownership in the hands of a narrow group,
	inheritance of decisive influence by family dynasties,
o	for example by:
	limiting the maximum share that any single entity may hold,
	prohibiting voting pacts that circumvent such limits.
The aim is to ensure that:
•	POL CAT remains an institution of work and knowledge,
•	and does not transform, over time, into a new centre of capital domination.
________________________________________
5.3. Regulation of the 10% Margin and Its Allocation
The 10% margin on the market price, divided into:
•	5% for remuneration of salespeople,
•	5% for remuneration of scientists,
must be clearly regulated by law in order to:
•	protect the mechanism against erosion and abuse,
•	give all participants legal certainty.
The law should therefore stipulate that:
1.	POL CAT’s margin is fixed at 10% of the market price of goods and services sold through its system:
o	any change to this rate:
	requires a legislative act,
	cannot be decided solely by the company’s internal bodies.
2.	Allocation of the margin is strictly defined:
o	5 percentage points of the price:
	form a fund dedicated exclusively to wages and bonuses of POL CAT sales personnel,
o	5 percentage points of the price:
	form a fund dedicated exclusively to wages and research costs of scientists working for or with POL CAT.
3.	Prohibition of transferring margin funds to capital purposes:
o	funds accumulated as part of the
	cannot be transferred to:
	dividend payments,
	speculative financial investments not serving the mission,
	unjustified management bonuses.
4.	Obligation of transparent accounting:
o	POL CAT must:
	keep separate accounts for:
	the salespeople’s fund,
	the scientists’ fund,
	publish annual reports:
	on income from margins,
	on their allocation to remuneration and research activities.
This gives society confidence that:
•	every purchase made through POL CAT directly finances work and science,
and not private enrichment of capital owners.
________________________________________
5.4. Protection of Transparency, Public Supervision and Democratic Governance
In order to maintain trust in POL CAT and to protect it against corruption, oligarchization or political capture, the legal framework should establish:
1.	High standards of transparency:
o	POL CAT is obliged to:
	publish:
	price structures (including the 10% margin),
	annual financial statements,
	reports on the use of funds for research,
	make these documents:
	easily accessible to the public,
	subject to external audit.
2.	Public and scientific supervision:
o	a Supervisory Council for POL CAT may be established by law, consisting of:
	representatives of:
	employees,
	scientific institutions,
	local governments,
	civil society organizations,
o	its tasks shall include:
	monitoring compliance with the mission,
	assessing the ethical dimension of operations,
	issuing opinions on strategic decisions.
3.	Democratic governance mechanisms:
o	legal rules should ensure that:
	the management of POL CAT is:
	appointed for limited terms,
	subject to removal in case of breach of the mission,
	employees and scientists have:
	real instruments to influence strategic directions
(e.g. via assemblies, elections of representatives).
4.	Whistleblower protection:
o	the legal framework should include:
	instruments protecting employees who report:
	abuses,
	corruption,
	deviations from the principles of the Third Way.
Through these mechanisms, POL CAT can function as:
•	a living example of democratic socio economic governance,
•	and not a closed technocratic or oligarchic structure.
________________________________________
5.5. Compatibility with National and European Union Law
The legal framework must also ensure that POL CAT is:
•	compatible with national economic, company and labour law,
•	and, in the case of EU Member States, compatible with EU law, in particular:
1.	Freedom of economic activity:
o	POL CAT must remain:
	an entity operating on the market,
	not a body of state administration,
o	but its special mission and non profit capital character:
	should be recognized as an expression of the freedom of association and economic initiative.
2.	Rules of competition and state aid:
o	any support granted to POL CAT by the State must:
	be limited and transparent,
	not distort competition beyond what is necessary to achieve objectives of general interest,
o	legal solutions may:
	rely on existing EU categories such as:
	services of general economic interest (SGEI),
	social economy enterprises.
3.	Internal market principles:
o	POL CAT should:
	respect the principles of free movement of goods and services,
	not impose unjustified restrictions on other entities,
o	its specific 10% margin model:
	is a self imposed internal rule,
and does not impose obligations on other companies.
4.	Labour and social protection standards:
o	the legal framework must comply with:
	EU and national standards regarding:
	labour law,
	non discrimination,
	social security,
o	at the same time, POL CAT may go beyond the minimum standards:
	as a positive example in the field of fair pay and social protection.
________________________________________
5.6. Constitutional Principles Supporting the Third Way
For the Third Way and POL CAT model to be stable in the long term, it is advisable to relate them to fundamental constitutional principles, such as:
1.	Social market economy:
o	POL CAT realizes:
	the idea that the market must serve society,
	and not vice versa.
2.	Protection of human dignity and work:
o	by eliminating capital profit as a dominant source of wealth,
o	and replacing it with remuneration for work and knowledge,
o	the system protects:
	the dignity of workers,
	the dignity of scientists.
3.	Principle of social justice:
o	the mechanism of prices and margins:
	reduces structural inequalities,
	prevents the emergence of extreme wealth based on other people’s labour.
4.	Freedom of association and economic activity:
o	POL CAT is an expression of:
	free choice of a model of economic organization by citizens,
	carried out within the framework of a democratic legal order.
In the long term, it may be considered:
•	to introduce into the constitution a general clause recognizing:
o	the legitimacy of socio economic institutions operating without capital profit,
in the name of social justice and peaceful evolution.
________________________________________
5.7. Evolutionary Path of Legal Implementation
In line with the spirit of the Third Way, the legal framework for POL CAT should be introduced evolutionarily, in several stages:
1.	Pilot stage:
o	adoption of a special act enabling the creation of POL CAT as a pilot socio economic institution,
o	limitation of its operation to selected sectors or regions,
o	close monitoring of:
	economic,
	social,
	and legal effects.
2.	Adjustment and expansion:
o	after evaluation of the pilot:
	adjustment of legal provisions,
	gradual extension of POL CAT’s competences,
	creation of:
	regional branches,
	sectoral versions (e.g. for food, medicines, energy).
3.	Integration with broader legal order:
o	adaptation of:
	tax law,
	public procurement law,
	regulations on research funding,
o	so that they:
	take into account the specificity of POL CAT,
	and do not discriminate institutions operating without capital profit.
4.	Internationalization:
o	initiation of a debate:
	in the European Union,
	in international organizations,
o	on recognizing:
	POL CAT type entities as a legitimate model of ethical economic activity.
This evolutionary path allows:
•	to avoid revolutionary shocks,
•	while consistently embedding the Third Way and POL CAT model in a stable legal structure.
________________________________________
KONCEPCJA TRZECIEJ DROGI I SYSTEM POL CAT
Abstrakt
Niniejszy dokument przedstawia prawne, ekonomiczne i etyczne ramy funkcjonowania POL CAT jako kluczowej instytucji Trzeciej Drogi. POL CAT jest zaprojektowany nie jako tradycyjna spółka kapitałowa nastawiona na zysk, lecz jako instytucja społeczno gospodarcza o znaczeniu publicznym, łącząca trzy zasadnicze funkcje: etyczną dystrybucję dóbr i usług, stabilne wynagradzanie pracy oraz systematyczne finansowanie nauki. Mechanizm cen i marż opiera się na cenach rynkowych: POL CAT sprzedaje po obowiązującej cenie rynkowej, a stała marża 10% od tej ceny pełni wyłącznie rolę narzędzia strukturalnego. Marża ta jest ściśle dzielona na dwie równe części: 5% przeznaczane jest na wynagrodzenia handlowców POL CAT, odpowiedzialnych za uczciwy i przejrzysty handel, a 5% na wynagrodzenia naukowców pracujących dla lub z POL CAT, którzy badają, monitorują i udoskonalają funkcjonowanie systemu. Żadna część marży nie może być wypłacana jako zysk kapitałowy ani dywidenda.
Proponowane ramy prawne dla POL CAT regulują jego szczególny status, strukturę własności oraz system zarządzania. Ograniczają lub wyłączają dochód kapitałowy, gwarantują demokratyczny udział pracowników i instytucji naukowych w nadzorze, a także wprowadzają silne wymogi przejrzystości, nadzoru publicznego i naukowego oraz wyodrębnionej ewidencji środków z marży. Model został zaprojektowany tak, aby był zgodny z prawem krajowym i regulacjami Unii Europejskiej, w tym z zasadami wolności działalności gospodarczej, konkurencji, pomocy publicznej oraz standardami prawa pracy. Jako głębszą podstawę normatywną przywołuje się zasady konstytucyjne: społeczną gospodarkę rynkową, ochronę godności człowieka i pracy oraz sprawiedliwość społeczną. Ścieżka wdrożenia ma charakter wyraźnie ewolucyjny: od specjalnej ustawy pilotażowej i ograniczonego zastosowania sektorowego, przez stopniową korektę i rozszerzanie zakresu działania, aż po integrację z szerszym porządkiem prawnym i potencjalne umiędzynarodowienie modelu POL CAT jako uprawnionej, etycznej alternatywy dla klasycznych spółek kapitałowych. W ten sposób POL CAT staje się praktycznym narzędziem pokojowej ewolucji społecznej, przekształcając część obecnej nadwyżki rynkowej w stabilne wynagrodzenie za pracę oraz w wiedzę służącą całemu społeczeństwu.
________________________________________
